{\cf2 Vlectra\par}

{\cf1\b 2. Executive Summary\par}
{\cf1\b 2.1 Sampling Methodology\par}
{\cf2\b0 Please note that the audit was conducted based on a sampling approach, meaning that findings and conclusions are based on a selected sample of processes and data, not on 100% evaluation. The goal is to provide reasonable assurance rather than absolute certainty. This methodology proved effective and enabled the organization to identify targeted improvement actions.\par}

{\cf1\b 2.2 General Impressions of the Management System\par}
{\cf2\b0 The ISMS at Vlectra demonstrates a strong commitment to information security, with comprehensive policies and procedures aligned to ISO/IEC 27001:2022 requirements. Management involvement is evident through regular reviews and clearly defined roles and responsibilities. Controls for organizational, people, physical, and technological domains are largely implemented and maintained effectively. However, some areas require further documentation and evidence to fully demonstrate compliance.\par}

{\cf1\b 2.2.1 Highlights\par}
{\cf2\b0
- Information Security Policy is well established, approved by management, and communicated across the organization.\par
- Access control, identity management, and authentication controls are robust, including two-factor authentication and formal user registration/de-registration processes.\par
- Incident management processes are comprehensive, covering detection, response, analysis, and learning.\par
- Supplier relationships and cloud service usage are managed with appropriate security clauses and controls.\par
- Business Continuity and Disaster Recovery plans are defined with clear roles, responsibilities, and recovery objectives.\par
- Security awareness and training programs are in place with high completion rates.\par
- Network security, cryptography, and system hardening practices are effectively implemented.\par
- Change management and secure development lifecycle processes are documented and enforced.\par
}

{\cf1\b 2.2.2 Findings\par}
{\cf2\b0
- Some controls lack explicit documented evidence, such as information classification and labelling, intellectual property rights compliance, and documented operating procedures.\par
- Remote working policies require enhancement to include detailed security controls, secure access methods, and monitoring.\par
- Physical security monitoring (e.g., CCTV, intrusion detection) is not explicitly documented.\par
- Controls for supporting utilities (power, HVAC) and environmental threat protections need further development and documentation.\par
- Data masking policies beyond testing environments are not formally documented.\par
- Protection of information systems during audit testing is not addressed in existing documentation.\par
- Equipment siting and protection controls require formal definition and documentation.\par
- Some evidence recommendations suggest inclusion of explicit approval records, documented procedures, and formal role/responsibility matrices.\par
}

{\cf1\b 2.2.3 Non-conformities identified\par}
{\cf2\b0
- Lack of documented evidence for information classification and labelling controls.\par
- Absence of formal documented procedures for intellectual property rights compliance.\par
- Missing documented operating procedures covering incident management, change management, backup, and recovery.\par
- No explicit documented controls for physical security monitoring such as CCTV or access logging.\par
- Insufficient documentation on protection against physical and environmental threats.\par
- No formal data masking policy covering all relevant environments.\par
- Lack of documented procedures to protect information systems during audit testing.\par
- Missing documented controls for cabling security and equipment maintenance.\par
}

{\cf1\b 2.2.4 Opportunities for improvement\par}
{\cf2\b0
- Develop and maintain documented information classification and labelling schemes with evidence of application.\par
- Establish formal procedures and evidence for intellectual property rights compliance.\par
- Document and authorize operating procedures for key ISMS processes including incident and change management.\par
- Implement and document physical security monitoring controls such as CCTV and access logs.\par
- Enhance Business Continuity Plan with detailed controls for supporting utilities and environmental safeguards.\par
- Create a comprehensive remote working policy addressing secure access, endpoint security, user responsibilities, and monitoring.\par
- Formalize data masking policies beyond testing environments.\par
- Develop procedures to ensure protection of information systems during audit testing activities.\par
- Provide documented controls and evidence for cabling security and equipment maintenance.\par
- Include explicit documented approvals, role/responsibility matrices, and evidence of policy enforcement as recommended.\par
